https://www.kaggle.com/ufffnick/loan-prediction-dream-housing-finance https://datahack.analyticsvidhya.com/contest/all/ https://github.com/ritusri/Loan-Prediction-Problem/blob/master/loan_prediction%20(1).ipynb

Caso de Estudio¶

Predecir la elegibilidad del préstamo para una empresa de financiación de viviendas "de ensueño".

La empresa Dream Housing Finance se ocupa de todo tipo de préstamos hipotecarios. Tienen presencia en todas las áreas urbanas, semiurbanas y rurales. El cliente primero solicita un préstamo hipotecario y luego la empresa valida la elegibilidad del cliente para el préstamo.

La empresa desea automatizar el proceso de elegibilidad del préstamo (en tiempo real) según los detalles del cliente proporcionados al completar el formulario de solicitud en línea. Estos detalles son género, estado civil, educación, número de dependientes, ingresos, monto del préstamo, historial crediticio y otros. Para automatizar este proceso, han proporcionado un conjunto de datos para identificar los segmentos de clientes que son elegibles para el monto del préstamo para que puedan dirigirse específicamente a estos clientes.

Variable Description¶

TRAIN

Loan_ID Unique Loan ID Gender Male/ Female Married Applicant married (Y/N) Dependents Number of dependents Education Applicant Education (Graduate/ Under Graduate) Self_Employed Self employed (Y/N) ApplicantIncome Applicant income CoapplicantIncome Coapplicant income LoanAmount Loan amount in thousands Loan_Amount_Term Term of loan in months Credit_History Credit history meets guidelines Property_Area Urban/ Semi Urban/ Rural Loan_Status (Target) Loan approved (Y/N)

TEST

Loan_ID Unique Loan ID Gender Male/ Female Married Applicant married (Y/N) Dependents Number of dependents Education Applicant Education (Graduate/ Under Graduate) Self_Employed Self employed (Y/N) ApplicantIncome Applicant income CoapplicantIncome Coapplicant income LoanAmount Loan amount in thousands Loan_Amount_Term Term of loan in months Credit_History credit history meets guidelines Property_Area Urban/ Semi Urban/ Rural

def saca_metricas(y1, y2):#con esto sacamos la matriz de confusion, curva roc y la pintamos.
    print('matriz de confusión')
    print(confusion_matrix(y1, y2))
    print('accuracy')
    print(accuracy_score(y1, y2))
    print('precision')
    print(precision_score(y1, y2))
    print('recall')
    print(recall_score(y1, y2))
    print('f1')
    print(f1_score(y1, y2))
    false_positive_rate, recall, thresholds = roc_curve(y1, y2)
    roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, recall)
    print('AUC')
    print(roc_auc)
    plt.plot(false_positive_rate, recall, 'b')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'r--')
    plt.title('AUC = %0.2f' % roc_auc)

def prop_check(data):
    f, axes = plt.subplots(6,2,figsize= (15,26))
    plt.suptitle('Train data, cantidad vs proporcion de cada variable respecto al estatus del prestamo', size =16, y = 0.9)
    col = data.columns[1:data.shape[1]-1]
    r = 0
    for i in col:
        if (data.dtypes == 'object')[i]:        
            data_prop = (data['Loan_Status']
                          .groupby(data[i])
                          .value_counts(normalize = True)
                          .rename('prop')
                          .reset_index())
            sns.countplot(data = data, 
                          x ='Loan_Status', 
                          hue = i, 
                          ax = axes[r,0], 
                          hue_order=data_prop[i].unique(), 
                          palette="ch:.25")
            sns.barplot(data = data_prop, 
                        x = 'Loan_Status', 
                        y = 'prop',
                        hue = i,
                        ax = axes[r,1],
                        palette="ch:.25")
            r = r+1
prop_check(data_set)

In [698]:
def categorize(df):
    df.Gender.replace({'Male': 1, 'Female': 0}, inplace = True)
    df.Married.replace({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0}, inplace = True)
    df.Education.replace({'Graduate': 1, 'Not Graduate': 0}, inplace = True)
    df.Self_Employed.replace({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0}, inplace = True)
    df = df.join(pd.get_dummies(df.Dependents, prefix='Dependents'))
    df.drop(columns= ['Dependents', 'Dependents_3+'], inplace=True)#dependents restantes respecto a si tiene 3 o mas dependientes
    df = df.join(pd.get_dummies(df.Property_Area, prefix='Property_Area'))
    df.drop(columns= ['Property_Area', 'Property_Area_Rural'], inplace=True)
    return df

Variables nuevas¶

Data Normalization Normalization is a rescaling of the data from the original range so that all values are within the new range of 0 and 1.

Normalization requires that you know or are able to accurately estimate the minimum and maximum observable values. You may be able to estimate these values from your available data.

Voy a evitar generar mayo variables categoricas dado que se trata de un modelo de categorización y por ejemplo los arboles crecerían en un solo sentido.

ln_monthly_return: El monto del prestamo respecto meses, normalizado. Puntualización habra que tratar LoanAmount y Loan_Amount_Term ln_total_income: Total de ingreso del hogar. suma de ApplicantIncome + CoapplicantIncome ln_LoanAmount: Normalizaciòn del loanAmount. SE ELIMINA loan Amount
In [717]:
def add_feat(df):
    ln_monthly_return = np.log(df.LoanAmount/df.Loan_Amount_Term)
    df['ln_monthly_return'] = (ln_monthly_return - np.mean(ln_monthly_return))/(np.std(ln_monthly_return)/np.sqrt(len(ln_monthly_return)))
    
    ln_total_monthly_income = np.log(df.ApplicantIncome + df.CoapplicantIncome)
    df['ln_total_income'] = (ln_total_monthly_income - np.mean(ln_total_monthly_income))/(np.std(ln_total_monthly_income)/np.sqrt(len(ln_total_monthly_income)))
    
    ln_LoanAmount = np.log(1000*df.LoanAmount)
    df['ln_LoanAmount'] = (ln_LoanAmount - np.mean(ln_LoanAmount))/(np.std(ln_LoanAmount)/np.sqrt(len(ln_LoanAmount)))
    ln_monthly_return = np.log(df.LoanAmount/df.Loan_Amount_Term)
    
    return df
In [718]:
data_set = add_feat(data_set)
In [719]:
test = add_feat(test)

Definicion de una función par ver como distribuyen las nuevas variables

In [723]:
def norm_plt(df):
    f, axes = plt.subplots(3,2,figsize= (12,15),squeeze=False)

    ###### total income ########
    sns.distplot(df.ln_total_income
                 ,ax=axes[0,0]).set_title('ln(total_income) norm distribution')
    #axes[0,0].set_xlim(-100,100)
    axes[0,0].text(0.03, 0.85,
                   'skew: {0:0.2}\nkurtosis: {1:0.2f}'
                   .format(skew(df.ln_total_income),
                                          kurtosis(df.ln_total_income)),
                   horizontalalignment='left',
                   verticalalignment='bottom',
                   transform=axes[0,0].transAxes,
                   bbox={'facecolor': 'white'})
    sns.distplot((df.ApplicantIncome+df.CoapplicantIncome),
                 ax=axes[0,1]).set_title('total_income distribution')
    axes[0,1].text(0.7, 0.85,
                   'skew: {0:0.2f}\nkurtosis: {1:0.2f}'
                   .format(skew(df.ApplicantIncome+df.CoapplicantIncome),
                           kurtosis(df.ApplicantIncome+df.CoapplicantIncome)),
                   horizontalalignment='left',
                   verticalalignment='bottom',
                   transform=axes[0,1].transAxes,
                   bbox={'facecolor': 'white'})

    ####### monthly return ###########
    sns.distplot(df.ln_monthly_return,
                 ax=axes[1,0]).set_title('ln(monthly_return) norm distribution')
    #axes[1,0].set_xlim(-100,100)
    axes[1,0].text(0.03, 0.85,
                   'skew: {0:0.2}\nkurtosis: {1:0.2f}'
                   .format(skew(df.ln_monthly_return),
                           kurtosis(df.ln_monthly_return)),
                   horizontalalignment='left',
                   verticalalignment='bottom',
                   transform=axes[1,0].transAxes,
                   bbox={'facecolor': 'white'})

    sns.distplot((1000*df.LoanAmount/df.Loan_Amount_Term),
                 ax=axes[1,1]).set_title('monthly_return distribution')
    axes[1,1].text(0.7, 0.85,
                   'skew: {0:0.2f}\nkurtosis: {1:0.2f}'
                   .format(skew(df.LoanAmount/df.Loan_Amount_Term),
                           kurtosis(df.LoanAmount/df.Loan_Amount_Term)),
                   horizontalalignment='left',
                   verticalalignment='bottom',
                   transform=axes[1,1].transAxes,
                   bbox={'facecolor': 'white'})

    ###### norm ln_LoanAmount ########
    sns.distplot(df.ln_LoanAmount
                 ,ax=axes[2,0]).set_title('ln(LoanAmount) norm distribution')
    #axes[2,0].set_xlim(-100,100)
    axes[2,0].text(0.03, 0.85,
                   'skew: {0:0.2}\nkurtosis: {1:0.2f}'
                   .format(skew(df.ln_LoanAmount),
                                          kurtosis(df.ln_LoanAmount)),
                   horizontalalignment='left',
                   verticalalignment='bottom',
                   transform=axes[2,0].transAxes,
                   bbox={'facecolor': 'white'})
    sns.distplot((df.LoanAmount),
                 ax=axes[2,1]).set_title('LoanAmount distribution')
    axes[2,1].text(0.7, 0.85,
                   'skew: {0:0.2f}\nkurtosis: {1:0.2f}'
                   .format(skew(df.LoanAmount),
                           kurtosis(df.LoanAmount)),
                   horizontalalignment='left',
                   verticalalignment='bottom',
                   transform=axes[2,1].transAxes,
                   bbox={'facecolor': 'white'})
    
    
    ####### adding grid to the graph#########
    for i in range(3):
        for j in range(2):
            axes[i,j].grid(b=True, which='both', axis='both', color='grey', linestyle = '--', linewidth = '0.3')

def propall(data): col=data.columns data[col].value_counts(normalize=True) for i in col: sns.barplot(data = data.i.value_counts(normalize = True).reset_index(), x = 'index', y = 'Married', palette=current_palette) plt.grid(b=True, which='both', axis='both', color='grey', linestyle = '--', linewidth = '0.3')

def propall(data): f, axes = plt.subplots(6,figsize= (12,20)) col=data.columns for i in col: if (data.dtypes == 'int64'[i]): sns.catplot(x= i , kind="count", palette="ch:.25", data=data)

Optimización de los clasificadores¶

En nuestro caso: clasificación binaria, la función "cross_val_score" utiliza la validación cruzada StratifiedKFold para reducir el efecto de sesgo en los datos desequilibrados. es un buen enfoque para los casos en que la distribución de la columna de destino está sesgada
In [774]:
def cv_check(X,y, CV):
    models = [
        RandomForestClassifier(criterion='gini',
                               n_estimators=50,
                               max_depth=11,
                               max_features=6,
                               random_state=42,
                               class_weight='balanced_subsample',
                               n_jobs=4),
        SVC(C=1, kernel='rbf', gamma='auto',random_state=42,class_weight='balanced'),
        LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs',
                           multi_class='ovr',
                           max_iter=500,
                           C=1,
                           random_state=42,
                           class_weight='balanced'),
        GaussianNB(),
        #LinearSVC(C=1, 
        #         max_iter=500,
        #          random_state=0),
        DummyClassifier(strategy='most_frequent',random_state=42)
    ]

    entries = []
    
    for model in models:
        Nombre_modelo = model.__class__.__name__
        print ("Currently fitting: {}".format(Nombre_modelo))
        accuracies = cross_val_score(model,
                                     X,
                                     y, 
                                     scoring='roc_auc', cv=CV, n_jobs=4)
        for fold_idx, accuracy in enumerate(accuracies):
            entries.append((Nombre_modelo, fold_idx, accuracy))
        cv_df = pd.DataFrame(entries, columns=['Nombre_modelo', 'fold_idx', 'roc_auc'])
        
    return cv_df
In [775]:
def cv_bp(cv_df, title, axes):
    axes.grid(b=True, 
              which='both', 
              axis='both', 
              color='grey', 
              linestyle = '--', 
              linewidth = '0.3')    
    sns.boxplot(x='Nombre_modelo', 
                y='roc_auc', 
                data=cv_df, 
                width = 0.5, 
                ax=axes,
                palette=current_palette).set_title(title)
    sns.stripplot(x='Nombre_modelo', 
                  y='roc_auc',
                  data=cv_df, 
                  size=5, jitter=True, 
                  edgecolor="grey", 
                  linewidth=1, 
                  ax=axes)
    plt.ylim(0.2,1)
    plt.savefig('{}.png'.format(title), format='png')
    #plt.show()

Utilizando grid search cross validation escaneamos para encontrar los valores optimos de las variables para cada modelo. The values chosen after several runs to get the optimum variables within the optimal range for the roc_auc as closer we can get to 1

RandomForest¶

In [778]:
def model_score(data_set, model, grid_values, scorers_list):
    X_train = data_set.drop(columns=['Loan_Status'])
    y_train = data_set['Loan_Status']
    
    clf_dict = {}
    
    for i, scorer in enumerate(scorers_list):
        clf_eval = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid=grid_values, scoring=scorer, cv=5)#, iid=False)
        clf_eval.fit(X_train,y_train)
        print('Grid best parameters for {0}: {1} scoring: {2}'
              .format(scorer, clf_eval.best_params_, round(clf_eval.best_score_,3)))
        clf_dict[scorer] = clf_eval
    return clf_dict

In [780]:
def model_score(train, model, grid_values, scorers_list):
    X_train = train.drop(columns=['Loan_Status'])
    y_train = train['Loan_Status']
    
    clf_dict = {}
    
    for i, scorer in enumerate(scorers_list):
        clf_eval = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid=grid_values, scoring=scorer, cv=5)#, iid=False)
        clf_eval.fit(X_train,y_train)
        print('Grid best parameters for {0}: {1} scoring: {2}'
              .format(scorer, clf_eval.best_params_, round(clf_eval.best_score_,3)))
        clf_dict[scorer] = clf_eval
    return clf_dict

The following are the main functions to run each model evaluation in the chosen best values

In [788]:
def mod_eval(df,predictions, predprob, y_test, title):
    # prints confusion matrix heatmap    
    cm = confusion_matrix(df.Loan_Status[y_test.index], predictions)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.3g', xticklabels=['No', 'Yes'], yticklabels=['No', 'Yes']).set_title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Real')
    plt.ylabel('Predict')
    
    print(classification_report(df.Loan_Status[y_test.index], predictions))
    
    f, axes = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize= (20,6),squeeze=False)

    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(df.Loan_Status[y_test.index], predprob[:,1])
    roc_auc = auc(fpr,tpr)
    axes[0,0].plot(fpr, tpr, lw=3)
    axes[0,0].set_title('{} ROC curve (area = {:0.2f})'.format(title, roc_auc))
    axes[0,0].set(xlabel='False Positive Rate',ylabel='True Positive Rate')
    axes[0,0].grid(b=True, which='both', axis='both', color='grey', linestyle = '--', linewidth = '0.3')

    precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, predprob[:,1])
    best_index = np.argmin(np.abs(precision-recall)) # set the best index to be the minimum delta between precision and recall
    axes[0,1].plot(precision,recall)
    axes[0,1].set_title('{} Precision-Recall Curve'.format(title))
    axes[0,1].set(xlabel='Precision', ylabel='Recall', xlim=(0.4,1.05))
    axes[0,1].plot(precision[best_index],recall[best_index],'o',color='r')
    axes[0,1].grid(b=True, which='both', axis='both', color='grey', linestyle = '--', linewidth = '0.3')
def model_training(classifier,df):
    clf = classifier
    t=df.drop(columns=['Loan_Status'])
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_tests = train_test_split(t,
                                                         df['Loan_Status'],
                                                         test_size=ts,
                                                         stratify=df['Loan_Status'])
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    return clf

rf = model_training(RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, 
                                           n_jobs=4, 
                                           n_estimators=50, 
                                           max_depth=max_depth,
                                           max_features=max_features),data_set)

                                                     data_set['Loan_Status'],
                                                     test_size=ts,

mod_eval(data_set, rf.predict(X_test), rf.predict_proba(X_test), y_test, 'RandomForest')

Definitivamente es uno de los mejores modelos. Precision, recall y f1-score por encima del 0.90. El area debajo de la curva ROC es amplia. Si una línea pasa por un punto en el casco convexo de la curva, entonces no hay otra línea con la misma pendiente que pase por otro punto con un intercepción positiva verdadera (TP) más grande. Por tanto, el clasificador en ese punto es óptimo bajo cualquier supuestos de distribución en conjunto con esa pendiente. El punto ideal en la curva ROC sería ser (0,100), es decir, todos los ejemplos positivos están clasificados correctamente y no hay ejemplos negativos. mal clasificado como positivo.

SCORE: 0.7638888888888888. max_depth=2 Y n_estimators=80 SCORE: 0.7638888888888888. max_depth=1 Y n_estimators=100 SCORE: 0.0.6944444444444444. max_depth=4 Y n_estimators=400 SCORE: 0.7638888888888888. max_depth=2 Y n_estimators=50 SCORE: 0.6875. max_depth=8 Y n_estimators=200 SCORE: 0.70. max_depth=8 Y n_estimators=50

Fewer boosted trees are required with increased tree depth.

Further, we would expect the increase complexity provided by deeper individual trees to result in greater overfitting of the training data which would be exacerbated by having more trees, in turn resulting in a lower cross validation score.

Otras aproximaciones¶

Me consta que los modelos de clasificación no se comportan bien mientras existan muchas variables categoricas. Procurare mantener unicamente las imprecindibles. Mientras que normalizaré todas las continuas.

En resumen¶

El modelo RandomForest obtiene el mejor resultado. Aunque, puede parecer un poco sobreajustado (overfitted) según la sesión de validación cruzada antes del último ajuste. El Dummy classifier es esencial para la verificación de la cordura a lo largo del análisis.
